>
  <h1>About SeveranceCalc</h1>

  <p>
    SeveranceCalc was built for the millions of Americans who receive a severance offer each year and have no idea whether it's fair. Most people encounter severance once or twice in a career — rarely enough to develop intuition about what's standard, what's negotiable, and what's a lowball offer dressed up in formal legal language.
  </p>
  <p>
    We built this tool to close that information gap. Our Severance Pay Estimator draws on BLS compensation data, SHRM benchmarking surveys, and real-world separation practice to give you an evidence-based range in seconds. No sign-up, no data collection, no upsell. Just a straightforward estimate based on the same benchmarks that HR departments and employment attorneys use internally.
  </p>
  <p>
    Beyond the calculator, our editorial team — led by SHRM-CP certified HR professional Sloan Whitfield and paralegal Blake Anders — produces practical guides on the topics employees actually need: how to negotiate, how severance is taxed, when the WARN Act applies, and what to review before you sign anything.
  </p>
  <p>
    Our readers include employees who've just received a separation notice, HR professionals who want to benchmark their policies, career coaches helping clients navigate transitions, and people who are simply curious about what they'd be entitled to if they were ever laid off.
  </p>
  <p>
    SeveranceCalc is published by The Click Lab. Our content is free, ad-supported, and editorially independent. We do not accept sponsored content, and advertising placement has no influence over what we write or how we calculate.
  </p>

  <p class="disclaimer">
    SeveranceCalc is an informational resource and is not a law firm. Nothing on this site constitutes legal advice. If you have received a severance offer, we strongly recommend consulting a licensed employment attorney before signing.
  </p>
